derlying Rn is replaced by a homogeneous group.The justification for this wider scope comes from two sources: 1) the theory of semi-simple Lie groups and symmetric spaces, where such homogeneous groups arise naturally as "boundaries," and 2) certain classes of non-elliptic differential equations (in particular those connected with several complex variables), where the model cases occur on homogeneous groups. The example which has been most widely studied in recent years is that of the Heisenberg group.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aFunctions of real variables. 0aHardy spaces. 0aLie groups. 7aMATHEMATICS / Complex Analysis.2bisacsh  a"admissible.  aCampanato space.  aCampbell-Hausdorff formul.  aChebyshev's inequality.  aConstants.  aDerivatives and multiindices.  aDilations.  aHardy space.  aHardy-Littlewood maximal function.  aHeisenberg group.  aLittlewood-Paley function.  aLusin function.  aMaximal functions.  aNorms.  aOther operations on functions".  aPoisson kernel.  aPoisson-Szegö kernel.  aarea integral.  aassociated (to a ball).  aatom.  aatomic Hardy space.  aatomic decomposition.  aball.  acommutative approximate identity.  aconvolution.  adilations.  adistribution function.  agraded.  agrand maximal function.  aheat kernel.  aheat semigroup.  aisotropic degree.  akernel of type.  alower central series.  anilpotent.  anonincreasing rearrangement.  anontangential maximal function.  ap-admissible.  apolynomial.  apolyradial.  apositive operator.  aquasinorms.  aseminorms.1 aStein, Elias M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton Mathematical Notes eBook-Package 1970-2016z9783110494921oZDB-23-PMN08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gr